  "prompt": "Does the recommended daily values for micro-nutrients the same for, say, a 110 lb woman and a 200 lb man just like macros?",
  "response": "No, the recommended daily values for micronutrients (vitamins and minerals) are not the same for individuals with different body weights, ages, and genders. Factors that influence micronutrient needs include:\n\n1. Age\n2. Gender\n3. Body weight\n4. Physiological state (pregnancy, lactation)\n5. Activity level\n6. Overall health status\n\nFor example:\n- Iron needs differ significantly between men and women\n- Calcium requirements change with age\n- Pregnant and lactating women need more of certain micronutrients\n- Older adults may require different levels of vitamins B12 and D\n\nRecommended Dietary Allowances (RDAs) and Dietary Reference Intakes (DRIs) provide specific guidelines that account for these variations. While macronutrient needs can be more closely estimated by body weight, micronutrient recommendations are more nuanced and individualized.\n\nConsulting a healthcare professional or registered dietitian can help determine the most appropriate micronutrient intake for an individual's specific needs.",
